enames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Torrington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name, mainly from Black, Great, or Little Torrington (Devon).","2  English: in Lincs and E Anglia from East or West Torrington (Lincs), recorded as  <i>Terintone</i> in 1086 and  <i>Tiringtuna</i> about 1115, or from Terrington (Norfolk), recorded as  <i>Tirintuna</i> between 1103 and 1131."],"variants":[{"name":"Tarrington","meanings":["1  English: locative name, variant of   Torrington  .","2  English: locative name, perhaps sometimes from Tarrington (Herefs), but there is no clear link between the 1379 example and the 18th-century Staffs and Lancs name cited below, which may instead belong with (1)."]},{"name":"Terrington","meanings":["1  English: locative name, in S Lincs and E Anglia a variant of   Torrington   (2).","2  English: locative name in N England from Terrington (NR Yorks)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":1,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":11,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Torrington was born in 1095, in Great Torrington, Devon, England, his father, Roger de Torrington, was 28 and his mother, Mrs. Roger de Torrington, was 23. He had at least 3 sons with Mrs. Robert de Torrington. He died in 1115, in his hometown, at the age of 20."},"et":{"1095–1115":"1095–1115","1095–1140":"1095–1140","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","1105–Male":"1105–Surnud","1109–1170":"1109–1170","1135–Male":"1135–Surnud","1067–1115":"1067–1115","1072–Female":"1072–Surnud","1090":"1090","Abt 1105":"umbes 1105","1096":"1096","1140":"1140","1095":"1095","1072":"1072","1170":"1170","1106":"1106","1105":"1105","1115":"1115","1135":"1135","1067":"1067","1109":"1109","Great Torrington, Devonshire, England":"Great Torringto